    relationalNote:
      "John identifies himself not as an apostle or a prophet but as 'your brother and companion in the suffering.' He writes from a position of shared vulnerability, not authority. And the first thing Jesus does when John collapses in terror is touch him — 'he placed his right hand on me.' The cosmic Christ still makes physical contact with a frightened old man. The relationship between the visionary and the audience is established as one of mutual suffering and shared witness. John isn't above the churches; he's alongside them.",
