    modernParallel:
      "In 1963, Martin Luther King Jr. wrote a letter from a Birmingham jail that reframed an entire nation's understanding of justice. John wrote Revelation from a prison island and reframed an entire empire's claim to divinity. The parallel is not accidental: resistance literature is almost always written from a place of confinement. The people with the clearest vision of what's wrong are often the ones the system has locked away.\n\nThe image of Christ walking among the lampstands speaks to every community that feels forgotten by the powerful. The churches of Asia Minor were tiny, marginal, largely working-class gatherings in a vast empire that didn't notice them. And the risen Christ says: I am here. I see you. I haven't gone anywhere. For congregations in neglected neighborhoods, for immigrant churches meeting in rented storefronts, for believers in countries where faith is surveilled — this vision says the most powerful being in the universe is walking among you right now, and he knows your name.\n\nThe command 'do not be afraid' is the most repeated command in Scripture, and it never appears in comfortable circumstances. It appears when everything around you suggests you should be terrified. It's not a denial of danger. It's a declaration of presence.",
