      "The letters to the seven churches are performance reviews from the risen Christ, and they are devastatingly specific. Ephesus gets high marks for endurance, doctrinal discernment, and hard work — and then gets gutted: 'You have forsaken the love you had at first.' They've become so good at being right that they've forgotten how to be warm. The church that checks every theological box but has lost its first love is a church running on fumes. Jesus threatens to remove their lampstand — not because they're heretical, but because they're loveless.\n\nSmyrna gets no criticism at all. They are poor, slandered, and about to face imprisonment and death. Jesus says, 'Do not be afraid of what you are about to suffer. Be faithful, even to the point of death, and I will give you life as your victor's crown.' This is not a prosperity gospel. This is a fidelity gospel. The reward for faithfulness isn't comfort; it's a crown — and the crown is given to people who die for it.\n\nThe two letters together form a devastating pair: Ephesus has orthodoxy without love; Smyrna has suffering with faithfulness. Jesus is less impressed by correctness than by compassion, and less concerned with comfort than with courage.",
