    summary:
      "Pergamum is described as the place 'where Satan's throne is,' and the phrase is not metaphorical for John. Pergamum was the administrative capital of Roman Asia, home to the earliest temple of the imperial cult in the province, a massive altar to Zeus on the acropolis, and temples to Athena, Dionysus, and Asclepius. The city was saturated with competing allegiances, and the Christians there lived right in the middle of it. They held fast to Jesus's name even when Antipas — described as 'my faithful witness' — was killed. But some in the congregation have been following the teaching of Balaam, which in context means accommodating to pagan practices, probably including participation in guild meals held in temples where meat was offered to idols.\n\nThyatira has the opposite problem. The church is growing in love, faith, service, and perseverance — they're doing better now than at the beginning — but they're tolerating a self-styled prophetess whom John calls 'Jezebel.' She's teaching that it's acceptable to eat food sacrificed to idols and to engage in sexual immorality, which likely means participating in the trade guild banquets that combined feasting, idol worship, and ritual sexuality. In a city dominated by trade guilds (Thyatira was a commercial center known for dyeing, textiles, and bronze work), refusing to attend guild meals meant economic suicide. 'Jezebel' offered a theological justification for going along to get along.\n\nJesus is having none of it. Both letters draw a sharp line: you can live in the empire, but you cannot let the empire live in you.",
